<bill id="DLM2995802" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="160" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Food Bill</title>
    <billtype xml:lang="en-NZ">Government Bill</billtype>
    <explnote id="DLM2995803" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" rule-after="yes" rule-before="yes" bill.no="160" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
      <heading>Explanatory note</heading>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>General policy statement</heading>
        <explnote.crosshead>Introduction</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill introduces substantial reforms to the regulatory regime for the safety and suitability of food. Once fully implemented, it will replace the Food Act 1981 and the Food Hygiene Regulations 1974. The Bill will also make consequential amendments to the Animal Products Act 1999 and the Wine Act 2003 to improve the interface of regulatory processes across food sectors.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Food presents a major risk to the health of humans because of the potential of food to transfer harmful organisms, chemical residues, and other contaminants to humans. The levels of food-borne illnesses in New Zealand are too high.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>If New Zealand is to safeguard against food-borne illness, the current regulatory regime needs to be recrafted to create an efficient, modern risk-management-based regulatory regime that ensures food meets appropriate safety and suitability standards.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Many food businesses recognise this need and have taken part in lengthy consultation processes during the development of the policy for the Bill.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Details of policy</explnote.crosshead>
        <explnote.subhead1>Purpose</explnote.subhead1>
        <explnote.subhead2>Objective of Bill</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>The policy objective of the Bill is to provide an efficient, effective and risk-based regulatory regime that manages domestic food safety and suitability issues.  The purpose of the Bill is to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>restate and reform the law relating to how persons trade in food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>achieve the safety and suitability of food for sale; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>provide for risk-based measures that—</text>
                <list>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>minimise and manage risks to public health;  and</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>protect and promote public health;  and</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                </list>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>provide certainty for food businesses in relation to how the requirements of this Bill will affect their activities; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>require persons who trade in food to take responsibility for the safety and suitability of that food.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill imposes a primary duty on all persons who trade in food to ensure that the food is safe and suitable.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead2>Principles underpinning regulatory controls</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>The following principles underpin the Bill:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the need to achieve the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the need to require persons who deal with food to take responsibility for the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the need to promote standards and control mechanisms that are, as far as possible, risk-based and science-based; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the need for efficiency and to minimise compliance costs; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the importance of ensuring that regulatory requirements are applied consistently and fairly across sectors and groups, depending on factors such as risk; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the importance of providing services in a co-ordinated and coherent manner as far as practicable.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead1>Scope</explnote.subhead1>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill sets out a comprehensive regime for food safety and suitability and applies to businesses producing food in New Zealand regardless of whether that food is intended for the domestic market or export. The Bill also places specific requirements on persons importing food to New Zealand for commercial purposes.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Where provisions for food safety and suitability exist under the Animal Products Act 1999 or the Wine Act 2003, the Bill clarifies how those other pieces of legislation interface with it and harmonises requirements and processes to ensure consistency where appropriate.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead1>Risk management framework</explnote.subhead1>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill establishes a risk management framework and provides for 4 types of risk-based measures—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>food control plans, registered with the relevant territorial authority or the Ministry; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>national programmes, registered with the relevant territorial authority or the Ministry as set out in regulations; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>monitoring programmes set out in regulations to impose monitoring measures; and </text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>food handler guidance (educative materials) produced by the Ministry or by territorial authorities.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>With the exception of food handler guidance, these measures are defined in the Bill as risk management tools, to which attach specific statutory obligations and requirements.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill requires all persons who trade in food to operate under a risk management tool assigned to their sector unless—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the person voluntarily operates under a food control plan; or</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the person is exempted from the requirement to operate under the risk management tool assigned to that person's food sector and may instead operate under food handler guidance.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Persons may be exempt if—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>they have a risk management programme or regulated control scheme under the Animal Products Act 1999; or</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>they have a wine standards management plan under the Wine Act 2003; or</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>food handler guidance is appropriate for them.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Food control plans set out an assessment of the risks to food safety and suitability and the processes that will be followed to manage those risks. Food control plans will either be off-the-peg food control plans based on templates developed by the Ministry or be custom-made food control plans developed by the food business.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Ministry will develop food control plan templates where there is commonality among products and processes across a significant number of food businesses and there are relatively low risks. Where a food control plan is required and the Ministry has not developed a template for the food business type, then a custom-made food control plan will be required.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>A national programme is a regulation designed to identify, control, manage, and eliminate or minimise hazards or other relevant factors for the purpose of achieving safe and suitable food.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>There are 3 national programmes, differing in the level of control or the set of requirements they impose. Accordingly, a level 3 national programme generally imposes a higher level of control on a food business than a level 2 or level 1 national programme, and a level 2 national programme general imposes a higher level of control than a level 1 national programme. Each national programme will apply to a number of food sectors.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Food handler guidance will be made available by the Ministry or by territorial authorities for small-scale accommodation such as bed and breakfasts, occasional activities such as fund-raising barbecues, cake stalls, and one-off events such as ethnic food festivals, and for organisers of other events that include the sale of food. Guidance materials will provide advice on good operating practices and how to eliminate or minimise risks.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead1>Responsibilities, functions, and roles</explnote.subhead1>
        <explnote.subhead2>Industry responsibility</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill provides that a person who trades in food must ensure that the food is safe and suitable. This duty applies irrespective of whether the person is required to have a food control plan or is covered by a national programme or operates under food handler guidance.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill requires food importers to register with the Ministry and makes it unlawful for an unregistered person to import food for commercial purposes, unless that person is importing the food through an agent who is a registered importer.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead2>Minister’s responsibilities</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>The Minister has a role in the food safety regime that includes—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>issuing national outcomes in relation to the performance by territorial authorities of their functions and duties, or the exercise of their powers, under this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>recommending the making of regulations; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>adopting joint food standards; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>issuing domestic food standards; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>appointing persons to conduct reviews of certain decisions made by the chief executive of the Ministry.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead2>Chief executive’s responsibilities</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>The chief executive of the Ministry has a role in the food safety regime that includes—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>providing advice to territorial authorities on the performance of their functions and duties, or the exercise of their powers, under this Bill to ensure that the purpose of this Bill is achieved; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>providing information to the food industry and the public on matters relating to the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>implementing, managing, monitoring, and auditing the risk-based measures for the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>performing the function of a registration authority; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>for the safety and suitability of food, developing standards and implementing those standards, any adopted joint food standards, and any domestic food standards; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>establishing and monitoring national outcomes, performance criteria, standards, and other requirements that must be met by territorial authorities, agencies, and persons who perform functions or duties and exercise powers under this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>implementing, managing, and monitoring the food safety regime for imported food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>dealing with applications for registration by importers; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>establishing and maintaining the public registers; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>monitoring compliance with the applicable requirements of this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>monitoring and implementing the enforcement system under this Bill and working collaboratively with territorial authorities and other regulatory bodies; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>co-ordinating the response to emergencies that may undermine the purpose of this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>conducting, on application, reviews of certain decisions made by relevant territorial authorities or designating the persons to conduct those reviews; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>conducting, on application, reviews of certain decisions made by persons acting under his or her delegated authority; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>carrying out any functions that are incidental and related to, or consequential upon, the roles set out above.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead2>Territorial authority responsibilities</explnote.subhead2>
        <para>
          <text>Territorial authorities have a role in the food safety regime that includes—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>delivering services that are needed to achieve the purpose of this Bill, including the provision of advice and the dissemination of information on matters relating to the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>facilitating the administration and performance of functions and activities that support the role of the chief executive under this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>contributing to the implementation and delivery of risk-based measures for the safety and suitability of food; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>performing the function of a registration authority; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>carrying out enforcement and other regulatory responsibilities under this Bill in respect of their district; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>carrying out the role of a recognised agency, if so recognised under this Bill; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>carrying out any functions that are incidental and related to, or consequential upon, the roles set out above.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead1>Compliance</explnote.subhead1>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill sets out a range of options to promote compliance with legislative requirements, food control plans, and national programmes.  These include—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>enforcement powers for food safety officers; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the ability of a District Court to issue compliance orders; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>enhanced penalties provisions.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill also provides a registration authority with the power to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>impose conditions on food control plans, subject to a right of review; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>suspend all or any operations under a food control plan or a national programme, subject to a right of review; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>cancel the registration of a food control plan, or the registration of a food business under a national programme, subject to a right of review.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.subhead1>Transition</explnote.subhead1>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill makes provision for the new legislative regime to be implemented progressively over a 5-year transition period. Different food sectors may switch to the new arrangements at different times depending on the date set by the Governor-General, by Order in Council, for the expiry of the authorised transition period for each food sector or each class of food sectors.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Current food safety programmes under the Food Act 1981 are deemed to be equivalent to food control plans under this Bill, and the Bill provides for a transition period before those programmes must be reviewed.</text>
        </para>
      </explnote.group>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>Part by Part analysis</heading>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 1</emphasis> is the Title clause.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 2</emphasis> is the commencement clause. It provides for the Bill to come into force on <changeable>1 July 2011</changeable>.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2995804">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">1  </label>
          <heading>Preliminary provisions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>This Part contains 4 subparts.</text>
          </para>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides an overview of the general scheme and effect of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 3</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>states that the purpose of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 4</emphasis>) is to—</text>
                    <list>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>restate and reform the law relating to how persons trade in food; and</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>achieve the safety and suitability of food for sale; and</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>provide for risk-based measures that minimise and manage risks to public health and protect and promote public health; and</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>provide certainty for food businesses in relation to how the requirements of the Bill will affect their activities; and</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>require persons who trade in food to take responsibility for the safety and suitability of that food; and</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                    </list>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out when the Bill generally applies (<emphasis style="italic">clause 5</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides that the Bill binds the Crown (<emphasis style="italic">clause 6</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 2</emphasis> relates to interpretation. In particular, it contains—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the main interpretation clause, which defines various terms used in the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 7</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the definitions of the following key terms:</text>
                    <list>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>food (<emphasis style="italic">clause 8</emphasis>):</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>food business (<emphasis style="italic">clause 9</emphasis>):</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>processing and handling (<emphasis style="italic">clause 10</emphasis>):</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>safety and suitability (<emphasis style="italic">clause 11</emphasis>):</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                      <item>
                        <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                        <para>
                          <text>sale (<emphasis style="italic">clause 12</emphasis>).</text>
                        </para>
                      </item>
                    </list>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>In general terms, the Bill applies to food for sale and food-related accessories. The Bill defines food to mean anything that is used, capable of being used, or represented as being used for human consumption (whether raw, prepared, or partly prepared). The Bill defines a food-related accessory to mean anything that is used, or represented for use, in or for the production, processing and handling, or sale of food.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 3</emphasis> sets out—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>certain principles that are intended to govern the relationships between the Minister, the chief executive, and territorial authorities in fulfilling their respective roles and responsibilities under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 13</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>certain principles that the Minister, the chief executive, and all territorial authorities must take into account in performing functions or duties, or exercising powers, under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 14</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>a general outline of the roles of the Minister, the chief executive, and territorial authorities under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 15 to 17</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 4</emphasis> states that the primary duty of every person who trades in food is to ensure that it is safe and suitable (<emphasis style="italic">clause 18</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>As noted earlier, the terms safety and suitability are defined in <emphasis style="italic">clause 11</emphasis>. Safety is defined to mean a condition in which food, in terms of its intended use, is unlikely to cause or lead to illness or injury to human life or public health. Suitability is defined to mean a condition in which matters such as the composition, labelling, identification, and condition of food are appropriate in terms of its intended use.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2995805">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">2  </label>
          <heading>Risk-based measures</heading>
          <para>
            <text>This Part contains 5 subparts. It relates to risk-based measures, which are the primary instruments under the Bill for ensuring that food businesses achieve safe and suitable food. Every person who trades in food must, subject to certain exceptions, operate the person's food business under the risk-based measure that applies to the food sector that the food business is in. There are 4 types of risk-based measures under the Bill. These are as follows:</text>
            <list>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>a food control plan:</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>a national programme:</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>a monitoring programme:</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>food handler guidance.</text>
                </para>
              </item>
            </list>
          </para>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>classifies food sectors into 3 risk classes (as specified in <emphasis style="italic">Schedules 1 to 3</emphasis>) based on, among other things, the level of risk that their activities pose to public health; and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>assigns a risk-based measure that generally applies to food businesses in each of those classes (<emphasis style="italic">clause 20</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>In addition, <emphasis style="italic">subpart 1</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enables the Governor-General, by Order in Council, to amend <emphasis style="italic">Schedules 1 to 3</emphasis> by, among other things, adding or removing the name or description of a food sector to or from a schedule (<emphasis style="italic">clause 21</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out rules for determining the risk-based measure that applies to a food business that is not classified in any of <emphasis style="italic">Schedules 1 to 3</emphasis> or a food business carrying out activities that overlap 2 or more food sectors (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 22 and 23</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarifies that an operator of a food business may choose to operate under a food control plan even if the risk-based measure that would generally apply to the food business is not a food control plan (<emphasis style="italic">clause 24</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out the requirement for every person trading in food to operate under the risk-based measure that applies to the food sector that the food business is in, unless certain specified exceptions apply (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 25 and 26</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 2</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out requirements about the nature, content, and effect of a food control plan; and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>requires the registration of food control plans (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 27 to 69</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>A food control plan is a plan to identify, control, manage, and eliminate or minimise hazards or other relevant factors for the purpose of achieving safe and suitable food (<emphasis style="italic">clause 28</emphasis>). A food control plan may be individually developed for each person or food business. Alternatively, it may be developed by a person or food business and then adopted and amended to suit the operations of some other person or food business (<emphasis style="italic">clause 29</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 3</emphasis> sets out requirements about the nature, content, and effect of a national programme (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 70 to 84</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>A national programme is a programme designed to identify, control, manage, and eliminate or minimise hazards or other relevant factors for the purpose of achieving safe and suitable food (<emphasis style="italic">clause 71</emphasis>). It is imposed by regulations and, if required, supplemented by specifications set by the chief executive of the Ministry (<emphasis style="italic">clause 72</emphasis>). An operator of a food business that is subject to a national programme is required to register the food business in accordance with regulations made under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 76</emphasis>). Those regulations may also prescribe requirements for the suspension, cancellation, or surrender of the registration of a food business that is subject to a national programme (<emphasis style="italic">clause 73</emphasis>). </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 4</emphasis> sets out provisions about the nature, content, and effect of a monitoring programme (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 85 to 90</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>A monitoring programme is used to impose, in certain specified circumstances, monitoring measures and related activities that are necessary, among other things, for determining the safety and suitability of food and for ensuring the effectiveness of the food safety regime (<emphasis style="italic">clause 86(1)</emphasis>). It may be imposed on any food sector even though the sector is already subject to other risk-based measures (<emphasis style="italic">clause 86(3)</emphasis>). It is imposed by way of regulations made under the Bill and, if required, by a notice issued by the chief executive of the Ministry (<emphasis style="italic">clause 88</emphasis>). </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 5</emphasis> sets out provisions about the nature and effect of food handler guidance (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 91 to 96</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>Food handler guidance is guidance issued by a registration authority (the chief executive of the Ministry or a territorial authority) about the steps that are necessary to achieve safe and suitable food. It is intended to be educative only and does not, on its own, impose any duties on a person or food business that is subject to it (<emphasis style="italic">clause 92</emphasis>). A person or food business that is subject to food handler guidance is not required to operate under a food control plan, national programme, or monitoring programme and is not subject to the verification requirements of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 93</emphasis>). </text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>A person who is not ordinarily in the business of trading in food but who organises a community-based fund-raising activity that involves trading in food is exempt from the requirement to operate under a registered food control plan or a national programme (<emphasis style="italic">clause 94</emphasis>). In addition, the chief executive or the chief executive's delegate may exempt any person, group of persons, or any type or description of food business within a food sector from the requirement to operate under a registered food control plan or a national programme (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 95 and 96</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2995806">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">3  </label>
          <heading>Food imported for purpose of sale</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 97</emphasis> states the purpose of this Part, which is to require the safety and suitability of food imported for the purpose of sale and to provide for the registration of certain importers of that food.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 98</emphasis> is an interpretation clause for this Part. It provides that a reference to food imported for the purpose of sale includes a reference to food that is imported for processing and handling and is subsequently exported.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 99</emphasis> provides that a person must not import food for the purpose of sale unless the person is a registered importer or is importing the food through an agent who is a registered importer. It also provides that the importation of food in a quantity that is more than that which a reasonable person would consider to be reasonably required for personal consumption must, unless the contrary is proved, be treated as an importation of the food for the purpose of sale.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 100</emphasis> enables a food safety officer to give any imported food a clearance for entry into New Zealand in certain circumstances. A food safety officer may give a clearance for entry unconditionally or subject to any conditions that the officer thinks necessary or desirable to achieve the safety and suitability of the food.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 101 and 102</emphasis> set out the duties of, respectively, an importer and a registered importer.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 103 to 112</emphasis> provide for various matters relating to the registration of importers, including—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>who must be registered (<emphasis style="italic">clause 103</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>how an application for registration is to be made (<emphasis style="italic">clause 104</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the powers of the chief executive in relation to an application for registration (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 105 and 106</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the criteria for approving an application for registration (<emphasis style="italic">clause 107</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>how long a registration remains in effect (<emphasis style="italic">clause 110</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the duty of a registered importer to notify the chief executive of any significant change in circumstances, including any matter that may result in the registered importer not meeting the criteria for registration (<emphasis style="italic">clause 112</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 113 to 116</emphasis> deal with the suspension of a registered importer's operations. The chief executive may, at any time, suspend all or any specified part of a registered importer’s operations for an initial period of up to 3 months if the chief executive considers that the food imported by the importer may pose a risk to human life or public health or that there are matters that cast doubt on the safety and suitability of the food. A registered importer may also voluntarily suspend all of the importer's operations for an initial period of at least 3 months, unless the chief executive approves a shorter period.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 117 to 122</emphasis> provide for the removal of an importer’s name from the relevant public register if the chief executive cancels, or records the surrender of, that importer’s registration.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2995807">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">4  </label>
          <heading>Provisions relating to recognition, territorial authorities, administration, and enforcement</heading>
          <para>
            <text>This Part contains 6 subparts.</text>
          </para>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis> provides for the recognition of agencies and persons who carry out certain functions and activities under the Bill. Under this subpart, the chief executive may recognise—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>agencies that are responsible for managing and carrying out verification functions and activities and other specialist functions and activities and agencies that may manage and supply recognised persons:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>persons who carry out verification functions and activities and other specialist functions and activities.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>In this context, verification (as defined in <emphasis style="italic">clause 7</emphasis>) includes the application of methods, procedures, tests, and other checks to confirm compliance with the applicable requirements of the Bill or compliance of a food business with a risk management tool.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis> also provides for—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the duties of recognised agencies and recognised persons (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 124 and 125</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the procedures, criteria, and other matters relating to the grant of recognition by the chief executive (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 126 to 137</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the suspension of the recognition of an agency or a person (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 138 to 140</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the removal of the name of a recognised agency or recognised person from the relevant public register on the withdrawal or surrender of the agency's or person's recognition (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 141 to 144</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the protection of the Crown, the chief executive, and any employee of the Ministry from any liability for loss arising through the actions or omissions of a recognised agency or recognised person (<emphasis style="italic">clause 145</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 2</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out certain functions and duties of territorial authorities under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 146 and 147</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enables the Minister to issue national outcomes in relation to the performance or exercise by territorial authorities of functions, duties, and powers under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 148</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides that a territorial authority may, under the Local Government Act 2002, transfer its functions, duties, and powers to another territorial authority or to a regional council if the other territorial authority or regional council agrees in writing to the transfer and is able to meet any national outcomes issued by the Minister (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 149 to 151</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides that a territorial authority may transfer its functions, duties, and powers to the chief executive if the chief executive agrees to the transfer (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 152 to 156</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out the power of the chief executive to monitor the performance of functions and duties and the exercise of powers by territorial authorities under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 157)</emphasis>:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides that the Minister may initiate a review of the performance of functions and duties and the exercise of powers by territorial authorities under the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 158 to 164</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 3</emphasis> sets out principles and methods (including fees, charges, or levies) in relation to the recovery of the direct and indirect costs of the Ministry in administering the Bill that are not provided for by money that is funded by the Crown for the purpose (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 170 to 184</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 4</emphasis> allows penalties to be imposed or, as the case may be, waived in relation to any unpaid fees, charges, or levies that are required to be paid to the Ministry (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 185 to 187</emphasis>). </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 5</emphasis> relates to offences. In particular, it—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>establishes an infringement offences regime (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 188 to 191):</emphasis></text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out offences against the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 192 to 213):</emphasis></text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out rules on criminal liability for offences under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 214 to 218</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>extends the time within which an information for an offence against the Act can be laid (<emphasis style="italic">clause 219</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>describes defences available in prosecutions under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 220 to 226</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>contains evidential rules for prosecutions under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 227 to 229</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides for certain presumptions to be used in prosecutions under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 230 to 234</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>deals with sentencing for offences prosecuted under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 235 to 242</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 6</emphasis> relates to powers and enforcement. In particular, it—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enables the chief executive of the Ministry to appoint food safety officers and suspend or cancel appointments (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 243 and 244</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>empowers the chief executive of the Ministry to give directions to protect the safety and suitability of food (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 245 to 256</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>specifies the powers of the chief executive of the Ministry to publish statements about the safety and suitability of food (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 257 and 258</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>gives the chief executive of the Ministry power to approve documents, materials, or facilities, or persons or classes of persons, if the approval is required by a requirement of the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clause 259</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out the powers of the chief executive of the Ministry to gather information (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 260 and 261</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out the powers of verifiers (<emphasis style="italic">clause 262):</emphasis></text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provides for the powers and duties of food safety officers (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 263 to 288</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>imposes controls on the issue and use of search warrants (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 289 to 300</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>describes the compliance order regime (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 301 to 313</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2995808">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">5  </label>
          <heading>Miscellaneous provisions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>This Part contains 8 subparts.</text>
          </para>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis> enables—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the Governor-General, by Order in Council made on the recommendation of the Minister, to make regulations to exempt certain things or certain classes of persons or operations from the application of all or any provisions of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clause 314</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the Governor-General, by Order in Council made on the recommendation of the Minister, to make regulations to exempt food that is to be exported to a destination other than Australia from the requirements of adopted joint food standards or domestic food standards and food that is to be exported to any destination from the requirements of any regulations made under <emphasis style="italic">clause 346</emphasis> or any notices made under <emphasis style="italic">clause 367</emphasis> (<emphasis style="italic">clause 316</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>the chief executive, by notice under <emphasis style="italic">clause 367</emphasis>, to exempt food that is to be exported from the same requirements, and with largely the same effect, as those described in <emphasis style="italic">clause 316</emphasis> (<emphasis style="italic">clause 318</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 1</emphasis> also exempts certain persons covered by the Animal Products Act 1999 or the Wine Act 2003 from the requirement to operate under a registered food control plan or a national programme (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 320 and 321</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 2</emphasis>—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>protects persons performing their functions or duties, or exercising their powers, under the Act from civil and criminal liability (<emphasis style="italic">clause 322</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enables the chief executive of the Ministry to delegate functions, duties, and powers under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clause 323</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>facilitates the review of decisions under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 324 to 330</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 3</emphasis> deals with information and consultation requirements. In particular, it—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enables the chief executive of the Ministry to collect information and impose controls on the disclosure of information (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 331 to 337</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>states rules on notifying persons of information under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 338 to 340)</emphasis>:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>requires the Minister and the chief executive to consult on matters under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 341 to 343</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 4</emphasis> provides for regulations to be made under the Act, including regulations about— </text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>standards in relation to food (<emphasis style="italic">clause 346</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>risk management tools and related matters (<emphasis style="italic">clause 347</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>grading schemes that provide consumers with information about the level of a food business's compliance with the food safety regime (<emphasis style="italic">clause 348</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>imported food (<emphasis style="italic">clause 350)</emphasis>:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>offences (<emphasis style="italic">clause 353</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>administrative matters (<emphasis style="italic">clause 354</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 5</emphasis> enables the Minister to—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>adopt joint food standards in order to give effect to New Zealand's obligations under the Australia–New Zealand Joint Food Standards Agreement (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 358 to 364</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>issue, in certain limited and exceptional circumstances,  domestic food standards separately from those set out in the Australia New Zealand Joint Food Standards Code (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 365 and 366</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 6</emphasis> provides for notices to be issued under the Act (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 367 to 372</emphasis>), including emergency notices for emergency or urgent situations that create a risk of death or serious harm to any person (<emphasis style="italic">clause 370</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 7</emphasis> contains transitional provisions that—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provide for food sectors to make their transition on a staggered basis from the existing requirements of the Food Act 1981, the Food Hygiene Regulations 1974, and the Food (Safety) Regulations 2002 to the new requirements of the Bill when enacted (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 373 to 378</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>explain the status of existing legislative requirements, food standards, and other matters on or after the enactment of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 379 to 384</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify when some of the new provisions of the Bill will apply (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 385 to 388</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>treat certain food safety programmes that are in force on the enactment of the Bill as deemed food control plans (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 389 to 392</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>explain the status of food businesses not previously covered by food legislation (<emphasis style="italic">clause 393)</emphasis>; and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>explain the status of approved auditors and agencies managing approved auditors under the Food Act 1981 on or after the enactment of the Bill (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 394 to 396</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>enable the making of regulations about transitional matters and the recovery of costs incurred during the transitional period (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 397 to 400</emphasis>); and</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provide requirements for notices issued by the chief executive in relation to transitional matters (<emphasis style="italic">clause 401</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Subpart 8</emphasis> deals with a miscellany of matters. In particular, it—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>states that <emphasis style="italic">Schedule 5</emphasis> contains further provisions on public registers (<emphasis style="italic">clause 402</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>sets out rules on the incorporation by reference of material in regulations, Orders in Council, and notices (<emphasis style="italic">clauses 403 and 404</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>explains the relationship between regulations, Orders in Council, and notices made under the Bill and local authority bylaws (<emphasis style="italic">clause 405</emphasis>):</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>states that <emphasis style="italic">Schedule 7</emphasis> contains consequential amendments, repeals, and revocations (<emphasis style="italic">clause 406</emphasis>).</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <explnote.subhead1>Schedules</explnote.subhead1>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 1</emphasis> describes the food sectors that are generally subject to a food control plan.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 2</emphasis> describes the food sectors that are generally subject to a national programme.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 3</emphasis> describes the food sectors that are generally subject to food handler guidance.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 4</emphasis> contains miscellaneous provisions for registrations and recognitions.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 5</emphasis> gives details about public registers.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 6</emphasis> elaborates on the incorporation of material by reference.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Schedule 7</emphasis> contains consequential amendments, repeals, and revocations.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
